ast to, what order/position, what the fish were feeding on, etc. This taught me a few very key aspects of catching and stalking fish.  Fishing during winter will also help sharpen your skills for spring fishing.  I tend to learn a bit about the holding spots and hatches that will come off later in the week, month, etc, and use that to my advantage, pretty much honing my skills in the winter to carry into the year.  <br>
Often, fishing can be at its easiest in the winter, if you know where and how.  That is not supposed to sound mythical, but rather like a small jig saw puzzle.  Midges can be quite productive year round, and of course sow bugs seem to always work, for buggers I tend to wait til spring.  Do you have any particular areas you have in mind on the Little Red?<br>
~Andrew <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bflyfishingarkansasandmissouri.showUserPublicProfile?gid=flyfishar>FlyFishAR</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 123<br> <font color=#000000>(2/26/03 8:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://boards.justflies.com/Images/4/4551Photo1.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Winter time techniques</span><hr size=1> By the way fish will hold in springs that enter the fishery in the cold winter months the same as they do in the warm summer months. If you know of spots where there is a spring that enters underwater those are some favorite holds. Obviously this is not as big of a deal close to the dam, but you can gain some advantage if you know of some of these down stream.<br>
<br>
John <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F9FBFD><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bflyfishingarkansasandmissouri.showUserPublicProfile?gid=softhackle@flyfishingarkansasandmissouri>softhackle</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 12<br> <font color=#000000>(2/26/03 12:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> this saturday on the little red</span><hr size=1> i'll probably fish on saturday at ritchie shoals or one of the walk-in areas like the dam or winkley shoals.  i've got a boat up at heber and i love fishing down around mossy shoals, but i've never done that this early in the year.  i may try midge fishing for the first time this weekend if my typical techniques aren't working.  thanks for the info <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bflyfishingarkansasandmissouri.showUserPublicProfile?gid=andrewcolley@flyfishingarkansasandmissouri>Andrew Colley</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Little Red River Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 38<br> <font color=#000000>(2/26/03 4:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: this saturday on the little red</span><hr size=1> Hey,<br>
Ritchie shoals is pretty nice.  There are a couple good holes which in the summer are great spots for some large bows, and up around John's pocket is some good fishing as well.   Tie up some of the flies I use, which are described in an earlier thread.  They work great.  Also try a few biot midges in black.  If you fish Winkley, the half-hackle in the earlier thread tied in size 16-20 should produce some fish when the sun peeks out and a few midges are comming off.  I fish it under a #8 split shot in the faster water and the bordering eddies, and especially in the drop offs(use a small white indicator*).  At Ritchie, a bead head larva lace pattern in tan on a scud hook works pretty well.  It is pretty easy to tie, secure thread, tie in larva lace, and wrap forward creating an even taper to the bead(silver, gold or brass), and whip finish.  THey are easy and a fairly popular pattern with about 7 different names.<br>
~Andrew <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm10.showPrevMessage?topicID=3.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <br><br><a self href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3.topic&index=4><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/addReply1.gif border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm10.emailToFriend?topicID=3.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm10.threadControl?topicID=3.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/deleteThreadFire.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands</a><br> <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm10.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=3.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/subscribe.gif width=20 height=20 border=0 alt="Click to receive email notification of replies"> Click to receive email notification of replies</a> <br>  <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm10.unsubscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=3.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/unsubscribe.gif width=20 height=20 border=0 alt="Click to stop receiving email notification of replies"> Click to stop receiving email notification of replies</a> <br> </td><td align="right" valign="top"></td></tr><tr align="right"><td colspan=2><form action=http://pub98.ezboard.com/BBSForum.jumpShowForum method=post><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="1"><tr><td><b>jump to:</b><select name=forumName><option valu